{{Otherships|HMS Swordfish}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=United Kingdom |Ship flag= {{Shipboxflag|United Kingdom|naval}} |Ship name= HMS ''Swordfish'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered=8 December 1893 |Ship builder=[[Armstrong Whitworth|Armstrong Mitchell & Co.]], [[Elswick, Tyne and Wear]] |Ship laid down=4 June 1894 |Ship launched= 27 February 1895 |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned=December 1896 |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship fate=Sold, 1910 |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption=<ref name="Friedman p290">Friedman 2009, p. 290.</ref> |Ship class={{Sclass|Swordfish|destroyer}} |Ship displacement=*{{convert|320|LT|t|abbr=on}} light *{{convert|355|LT|t|abbr=on}} deep load |Ship length=*{{convert|200|ft|0|in|m|abbr=on}} [[length between perpendiculars|pp]] *{{convert|204|ft|3|in|m|abbr=on}} [[overall length|oa]] |Ship beam= {{convert|19|ft|0|in|m|abbr=on}} |Ship height= |Ship draught= {{convert|7|ft|9|in|abbr=on}} |Ship propulsion=*8 Yarrow water-tube boilers *4-cylinder [[Marine_steam_engine#Triple_or_multiple_expansion|triple-expansion steam engines]]<ref name="eng p422"/> |Ship power={{convert|4500|ihp|kW|abbr=on}} |Ship speed={{convert|27|kn|lk=in}} |Ship range= |Ship complement= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament=*1 × [[QF 12 pounder 12 cwt naval gun|12 pounder gun]] *3 × 6 pdr guns *2 × 18 in [[torpedo tube]]s |Ship armour= |Ship notes= }} |} '''HMS ''Swordfish''''' was one of two {{Sclass-|Swordfish|destroyer}}s which served with the [[Royal Navy]]. She was launched on February 27, 1895 by [[Armstrong Whitworth|Armstrong Mitchell and Co]] at [[Elswick, Tyne and Wear|Elswick]]<ref>''[[The Times]] (London)'', Thursday, February 28, 1895, p.4</ref> and sold off in 1910.
==Construction== HMS ''Swordfish'' was ordered on 8 December 1893, the first of two "Twenty-Seven Knotter" destroyers ordered from [[Armstrong Whitworth|Armstrong Mitchell and Co]] as part of the 1893–1894 construction programme for the [[Royal Navy]],<ref name="Lyon p85">Lyon 2001, p. 85.</ref> with in total, 36 destroyers being ordered from various shipbuilders for this programme.<ref name="Lyon p19">Lyon 2001, p. 19.</ref>
''Swordfish'' was laid down at Armstrong's, [[Elswick, Tyne and Wear|Elswick]], [[Newcastle-on-Tyne]] shipyard on 4 June 1894.<ref name="Lyon p85"/> Construction was delayed by industrial action and was not launched until 27 February 1895.<ref name="Brooke p172-3">Brooke 1999, pp. 172–173.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Sources differ as to the launching date. Chesneau and Kolesnick<ref name="conways60 p93">Chesneau and Kolesnick 1979, p. 93.</ref> and Friedman<ref name="Friedman p302">Friedman 2009, p. 302.</ref> state ''Swordfish'' was launched on 27 ''March'' 1894, while Lyon<ref name="Lyon p85"/> says 7 June 1894, the date given for the launch of ''Swordfish''{{'}}s sister ship ''Spitfire'' in other sources.<ref name="Brooke p172-3"/><ref name="conways60 p93"/><ref name="Friedman p302"/>|group=lower-alpha}} Sea trials began in March, but excessive vibration caused one of the ship's propeller shafts to be bent. A further attempt at trials in July suffered the same problem, and re-balancing of the ship's machinery was required to resolve the vibration problems. When trials were again attempted, [[Fouling#Macro fouling|fouling]] of the ship's hull resulted in the contract speed of 27 knots not being reached,<ref name="Brooke p173">Brooke 1999, p. 173.</ref> although, eventually, ''Swordfish'' managed to reach an average speed of {{convert|27.117|kn|mph km/h|annr=on}} during her official three-hour trial, when her engines generated {{convert|4750|ihp|kW|abbr=on}}.<ref name="eng p422">''The Engineer'' 23 April 1897, p. 422.</ref> ''Swordfish'' was not finally accepted until December 1896, 21 months after the contracted date of 31 March 1895.<ref name="Lyon p85-6">Lyon 2001, pp. 85–86.</ref>
The two Armstrong-built Twenty-seven knotters were not popular in service,<ref name="Lyon p86">Lyon 2001, p. 86.</ref><ref name="Friedman p44">Friedman 2009, p. 44.</ref> with Armstrongs not being invited to tender for the Thirty-knot destroyers required in the next few shipbuilding programmes.<ref name="Lyon p24">Lyon 2001, p. 24.</ref><ref name="Brooke p171">Brooke 1999, pp. 171.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Armstrongs built a 30-knotter destroyer in 1898–1899 as a stock vessel (i.e. without an order), which was sold to the [[Chilean Navy]] and named {{ship|Chilean destroyer|Capitan Thompson||2}} in 1902.<ref name="Brooke p173-4">Brooke 1999, pp. 173–174.</ref> The [[steam turbine|turbine]]-powered destroyer {{HMS|Cobra|1899|2}}, built as a stock vessel in 1898–1899, was sold to the Royal Navy in 1900, but ''Cobra'' sank while being delivered.<ref name="Brooke p174-5">Brooke 1999, pp. 174–175.</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}
==Operational history== ''Swordfish'' was based at [[Chatham Dockyard|Chatham]] in 1901,<ref name="nmm">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmg.co.uk/upload/pdf/Warship_Histories_Vessels_iv.pdf|title=NMM, vessel ID 377070|work=Warship Histories, vol iv|publisher=[[National Maritime Museum]]|accessdate=11 August 2013}}</ref> also serving at [[Sheerness]] and [[HMNB Portsmouth|Portsmouth]].<ref name="Brooke p173"/> In April 1902 she had finished a refit at Sheerness, and was commissioned at Chatham by Lieutenant and Commander J. W. E. Townsend the following month.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Thursday |date=1 May 1902 |page_number=6 |issue=36756| }}</ref> She received the crew of the destroyer {{HMS|Avon|1896|2}}, taking that ship´s place in the [[Medway]] Instructional Flotilla.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Naval & Military intelligence|day_of_week=Monday |date=28 April 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36753| }}</ref>
While most of the 27-knotters mounted their full armament of 1 × 12 pounder (76&nbsp;mm) gun, 5 × 6-pounder guns and two 18-in torpedo tubes, ''Swordfish'', owing to concerns about stability, tended to only carry a single torpedo tube.<ref name="Lyon p99-0">Lyon 2001, pp. 99–100.</ref> By 1905, it was stated by the Rear Admiral (Destroyers), that ''Swordfish'' was one of a number of destroyers that were "..all worn out" and that "every shilling spent on these old 27-knotters is a waste of money".<ref name="Lyon p116">Lyon 2001, p. 116.</ref> The ship's speed dropped during service, with maximum speed falling to {{convert|18+1/2|kn|mph km/h}} by 1909.<ref name="Brooke p173"/>
''Swordfish'' was sold for scrap to [[John Cashmore Ltd]] of [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Wales]] on 11 October 1910.<ref name="Lyon p86"/>
